Independent of the parallel tests carried out with the NKÚ in the years 2003 to 2005, the BRH had examined the economic viability of the planning and construction of the A 17 motorway.
He noted that the authority responsible for the approval required an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A-17.
The BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the road construction administration in the course of the examination of the superiority of the landscape tunnel.
As a result, € 10 million in construction costs and € 150,000 in annual operating costs were avoided.
When examining the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction was insufficiently prepared.
The following example illustrates this:
In the planning phase, the road construction administration waived the condition of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschener wall, as it was difficult to access it.
It was only when the tunnel Drivage reached the wall that it did so.
It was found that the Rock was more weathered than was assumed at the invitation to tender.
Extensive measures such as anchorages, injections and rock-impact nets for around€ 3.3 million were necessary.
The road construction administration not only paid the costs for additional ice-making facilities, which were already required, such as the securing of the Dölzschener wall, but also for those which would not have been necessary in the event of proper construction preparation.
This includes expenditure due to disrupted construction processes (€3.2 million), additional training of the heading team (€0.5 million) and higher wages and material prices due to the extension of construction time (€7 million).
This additional expenditure of around€ 10.7 million is not offset by any permanent added value.
The BRH took these and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to take better account of the specialist supervision for large road construction measures.
In this context, it should be stressed that the road construction authorities introduce quality assurance systems.
